London Arthur Anneslay
S. in answer taye of 17: past, I have sold most part of our last goods
& to patt off the rest I must needs be assorted of 2 bales of serges vr
one bale th cont. i5 gold cullours & 10 sparrawe grayes according to the inclosed
pattarnes cloth sarges of 22 y aays broad of 45 to a8 st ap. besidev an
other baleto cont 25 serves 22 yd assorted to the sume patt in callons
& 5„24 yd muskes, of the best goods that are to be had, therefore
limit no prijses for that bale I observe that you shall want
mony which I can hardely beleave because I supose monyes plertje
cnough with you yett never the less for ferare itt might be so shall
do all what I can to suply yd occasion in order where nat dosend
here inclosed a remise for £100: s du withen a month, att hhe
charge of georgue barous att 35:6 & lest then 3 welkes shall endeavour
to send asmuch for yd acctt att sicht, for I desire you not to draw on
mee & if you exarmim yd acctt. you will finde itt cleared of last
yeare with the last bill of £50:-:- so that this £100: is on this
yeares cctt. & what hence forward I shall frither remitt, & p nextsend
yd acctt curitt without faile pray faile not to morder the serges whilst
memorandem for mr. word to provire 25 cloth serges to the se pats
of 22 yd & ago broad good goods of 45 to 4813-

posssibly I could provided yd in ordered parcell of laces which is made
un in 2 packetts N. 4 beeng sent away yeasterday to come with these
Petters &N.5 will gop next, this parcell will shew you, that our
worckeromen can hordely live by makeing them for they are
as cheap asever laces were, so hove they will qive good content &
in corrigment for more, god send them sake to yd handes the while
doth antt to ƒ948:12 n £1582:- according to the inclosed invoy
for which please to give mee creditt if finde the opportunito

Sr my last to you was on the 18: t & according I promised do now
endeavour to cleare the acctt. of GV de seased before this geares
end in order where unto do here inclosed remitt you £107:10 „¾
sts att the charge of frr. Rayns ford of 127b 3 uso att 35:5 for
which att due day please to procure the needfull & note accordingly
be confident that the mony shall be remitted as soone as Ireceaued
itt, for I long as much as any of the heires, to be discharged, butt
the continuall alarmes here of the french pretences, do keep
eack boath mony & trade bij ond all exspectations & to great
greef of all the countrey for I do not beleave that times were
ever worse then they are now with us here, therefore you
may be sure that itt is not my fault that mony es so long
detained butt that I am with my respecte nuo
London Henry Maynard
Sr. my last to you was on tha 25:th past. sence recd. yd of 14 ditto god
be thancked I am almost restored to formar disposition though not
altoghether in strenght haveing lost so much blood I have payt mr. badier
only ƒ 1618:10 so to aggree p lease to have out the ½ stiver I have alsoo
discoursed him, when heshewd mee m. furnase his letter & order
to furnish him about 1000 Crownes which I tolo hem I should
pay him as soone as Ireis order & haveing sence rec od wrott
hime the needfull which then shall be hast to yd acctt & advised
the cust some the bayes from hull do tarry vere long if they were
here I could sell them all in 3 a 4 duyes time butt if the
tarry muck longer I doubt that then they shall bye by the walles
noother vessels yett arrived from England, wee have had vere for my weathe
of late yett hope that no missortune happened to any please p. first
to buy 5 ww Reds & 5 E yallow marck s pack whites & make of
each sort a nach to be wraeped with 2 bayes sach I hope the 6N. silver
markes shipped by this time as also the frises & de vouthire bays with
4 or 8 swanskins for which all I am much in haste as for auroras lead
them there, till more pleaty & better cheap: praydo as much you cando
have the pack whited att the lowest rate & well conditioned not spotted h
threadwaren in the back as often I have had on all which I do depend
I shall further do al I can to remitt you for my acctt. whist I ras soill
mij man mad up the acctt. of sales & some mis takes in them which
shall bo rectefied & sent you p next with the sale of ooto b. oursale beyine
to decreuse, & I am sure there is herdely one pack of drapperie comes
from England hether butt that I know off itt & I finde that god
be thanched, I have avere good share insale aswell as the best & that no
perticular remands mode goods then, butt there been so many makes
the trade to every one buttt little pr kent serves & Did sons sence
serve the Roosendael, as also one Pauwels, who exeept in the bussgns
of shar mr Demont leaves off trade & had no goods longe sence ur.
vudard recd one or 2 packes butt sence his wife dyed of late lest of
cloeth trade so the new beginner is Beydaels, assisted of mad bouw
servant, butt he beeng a shop keeper made great nrice att first & is
sil ready weary of itt beeny not fitt for a shopkeeper much less for a
mart: so that finde no preiudice to you in the hefleast as I shall
shew you when a & see you whist nown
th
Londen Abbram vivian
S. my last to you dras on the 25: past wath a remise for £28:13:1 on
Janiel porten for my acctt. sence have rec. for boath yd of 14814
ditto I could wish pindar was arrived, for I do much want the bayes I hope
you neglen ted not to in order 60p. more fomy formar directions
which ought to be ready by this time though I had never any perticiculitie
from you about them sevce, our sale hath been indifferent well all
our ket sies are almost sole all the bayes and most part of the cloathes
mall beeng heberto about 30 resting the proffitt I hope will giuce you
content, for you may assure yds self that no endeavour is wanting
onmy side to adrance boath air intrest which shall be ready
to shew you when yon come over & though you should not come yett
att the latter end of the yeare I ballance my bookes & the shallsend
you all acctt. in the menne while I am not be hinde in my bookes
& dofinde that onmy actt. with the last remise I am even included
ill the invoyces you sent mee now if the 60 bayes be bought in that
you could be in disbourse, for more goods I know not that be a provied
as for yd acctt. if you examin well you will see that the goods sold
to ylr. xb last are paye & £1180:- flemish up on acctt of this
yeare sall & after that rate you will finde vere neare 3 returnes
in 2 yeare so I should wonder what reason you can have of drawing
whene you finde mee so deligent to susely you &endeavourding to
promite yd intrest which I do not att alle finde in drawny whoever
my will is good to remitt you, butt amnday I am to pay gd bill
of go aug for £200: so must henis paticittie yett untriu I have
still good comimissions from others for lces & amonghst the rest them
nett aparcell of about ƒ0000:- which I keeply mee if you could
beserved with yett mee thinckes they are is cheaper then ever
I sent & so cutious assorted that itt can not be other wise thought
truly the werckerom, can not leother thoiught truly
live off itt lett mee know in answer here of if I shall send them
to you for iintwentie yeare they can not be better cheap as soone as
can shall remitt you againe whist now
